{{Infobox bus accident | title = 2011 Gansu school bus crash | date = 16 November 2011 | location = [[Zhengning County]], [[Gansu]], [[China]] | deaths = 21 including 19 children }}
On November 16, 2011, a [[school bus]] run by a private [[kindergarten]] [[head-on collision|collided head-on]] with a coal truck in [[Zhengning County]], [[Gansu]], China. 19 children were killed, as were 2 adults.<ref name=arrest>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/story/2011-11-20/China-bus-crash-kids-arrest/51325730/1|title=China arrests head of school that ran packed bus|work=USA TODAY|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> The bus was originally a nine-seat van, but it had been modified to carry more passengers, and was severely overcrowded; 62 children were on board at the time of the crash, along with the 2 adults.<ref name=arrest/> The government immediately closed the school and opened a public one in its place, with a 45-seat bus donated by an oil company.<ref name=arrest/> The school's owner, Li Jungang, was arrested on "suspicion of causing traffic casualties"; the parents of each child killed were to be awarded 436,000 [[Chinese yuan|yuan]] in compensation.<ref name=arrest/>
The accident caused a great deal of outcry on the Chinese internet, with many posters criticizing the small amount of money spent on education.<ref name=VOA>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.voanews.com/china-wangre/2011/11/21/gansu-school-bus-crash-sparks-anger/|title=Gansu School Bus Crash Sparks Anger|publisher=|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref> Further criticism was leveled at the government when it was announced shortly after the crash that China would donate 23 school buses to [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]]; many [[microblog]]gers questioned the propriety of donating decent vehicles to a foreign country while subjecting Chinese children to substandard conditions.<ref name=VOA2>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/english/news/asia/east-pacific/Chinese-Netizens-Question-Donation-of-School-Buses-to-Macedonia-134589298.html|title=Chinese Netizens Question Donation of School Buses to Macedonia|work=VOA|accessdate=9 April 2016}}</ref>
