{{Infobox recurring event | |name=Kentucky Apple Festival |logo= |image=Paintsville Lake Kiwanis Trail.jpg |caption= |location=[[Paintsville, Kentucky|Paintsville]], [[Kentucky]], [[United States]] |years_active=1962&ndash;present |dates=First weekend in October |genre=[[Horticultural]] |website=[http://www.kyapplefest.org Kentucky Apple Festival] }}
The '''Kentucky Apple Festival''' is an annual [[festival]] held in [[Paintsville, Kentucky|Paintsville]], [[Kentucky]] during the first Friday and Saturday in October. The festival was originally created in 1962 as a way to provide a market for the county's [[apple]] production.<ref name=festival>{{cite book |author=Shermanski, Frances |title=''A Guide to Fairs and Festivals in the United States'' |year=1984 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location=[[Santa Barbara, California]] |isbn=0-313-21437-9 |chapter=}} Retrieved on 2010-09-04</ref>
==History==
The first Kentucky Apple Festival was held on October 6, 1962, and was known as "Apple Day". It was guided by Elmon Davis, an officer at [[Citizens National Bank (Eastern Kentucky)|Citizens National Bank]] and apple orchard owner from [[Flat Gap, Kentucky|Flat Gap]]. Davis not only created the festival to promote the county's apple production, but to compete with the Johnson County Fair, which had been held annually since 1914. Eventually, the Kentucky Apple Festival became the more popular of the two and the Johnson County Fair became nonexistent.<ref name=johnson>{{cite book |author=Johnson County Historical Society |title=''Johnson County, Kentucky:History and Families'' |year=2001 |publisher=Turner Publishing Company |location=[[Nashville, Tennessee]] |isbn=1-56311-756-8 |chapter=}} Retrieved on 2010-09-04</ref>
==Traditions==
Although the majority of the festivities occur on the first Friday and Saturday in October, many events occur during the last week of September, adding up to over forty-five events. Traditional events include: Junior and Miss Apple Blossom pageant; school competitions in spelling, art, penmanship, and mathematics; old-fashion costume contest; [[diamondback terrapin|terrapin]] trot (turtle race); multiple concerts; car shows; Ducky Derby ([[Rubber duck]] race on [[Paint Creek (Johnson County, Kentucky)|Paint Creek]]) and the Apple Festival Parade.<ref name=official>[http://www.kyapplefest.org/ Kentucky Apple Festival] Official website. Retrieved on 2014-05-10</ref> One of the festival's largest and most popular events prior to 2009 was the Apple Bowl. The annual football game between [[Paintsville High School]] and [[Johnson Central High School]] was halted after 2008 due to the difference in the size of the two schools.
